Packet classification for mobile applications¶

We have developed the project related to the classification of encrypted packets. In the following we are going to find an algorithm that classifies different actions of a given application. The data structures that we have chosen to evaluate the results are a random forest and a neural network.

In the following box we read the dataset from a file, then we filter it given a specific application. Firstly, we have to set the path of the dataset, and the application that you want to investigate. Possible choice of application are:

facebook¶

twitter¶

evernote¶

We consider only the action with more occurances in the dataset, the threshold is calculated dynamically according to the number of sample. We have labeled all the rare action as 'other'. At the end we define all the other features, that we need to calculate later on.

#Load the dataset
data = pd.read_csv(path_dataset)

#Select only the packet realted to a specific application
app = data.loc[data['app'] == application]

#Define the minimum number of sample for each action
max_length = 1200
final_length = 400
step = 20

min_number_label = 15
max_number_label = 19

for index in range(final_length, max_length, step):
    app_filtered = app.groupby("action").filter(lambda x: len(x) > index)
    #Save all the action
    allowed_list = app_filtered.action.unique()
    if(len(allowed_list)>=min_number_label and len(allowed_list)<=max_number_label):
        final_length = index
        break

print("Value for length: ",final_length)

#We classify as other all the other action
app.loc[~app["action"].isin(allowed_list), "action"] = "Other"

#Cleaning the index value associated to the sample
app = app.reset_index()
app = app.drop(columns=["index"])

#Feature to add to each sample
app['Num_flow'] = 0
app['Duration'] = 0
app['Avg_flow_length']=0
app['Mean_block']=0
app['Var_block']=0
app['Position']=0
app['Shift_from_start']=0

#Definition of the type of the previous feature
app['Avg_flow_length'] = app['Avg_flow_length'].astype('float64') 
app['Mean_block'] = app['Mean_block'].astype('float64') 
app['Var_block'] = app['Var_block'].astype('float64') 
app['Shift_from_start'] = app['Shift_from_start'].astype('float64') 
app['Duration'] = app['Duration'].astype('float64')

Functions used to evaluate for each sample mean and variance. We use as a feature the mean and the variance of the packets for each flow. We evaluate a weighted mean and variance. Weigth is define to give more importance to incoming packets than the outgoing packet.

In [4]:
#Weight
w_pos = 0.67
w_neg = 0.33

def media(array):
    a = ast.literal_eval(array)  
    sum = 0
    w_sum = 0
    for i in a:
        i=float(i)
        if(i>=0):
            sum+=w_pos*i
            w_sum+=w_pos           
        else:
            i=-i
            sum+=w_neg*(i)
            w_sum+=w_neg       
    return (sum)/(w_sum)


def variance(array, media):
    array = ast.literal_eval(array)
    media = float(media)
    sum = 0
    w_sum = 0
    for i in array:
        i=float(i)
        if(i>=0):
            sum+=  ((i-media)*(i-media))*w_pos
            w_sum+=w_pos            
        else:
            i = -i
            sum += ((i-media)*(i-media))*w_neg
            w_sum+=w_neg            
    var2 = (sum)/(w_sum) 
    var_rad = np.sqrt(var2)
    return var_rad

#Set the value of mean and variance using previous functions
app['mean'] = app.apply(lambda x: media(x['packets_length_total']), axis=1)
app['variance'] = app.apply(lambda x: variance(x['packets_length_total'],x['mean']), axis=1)

In the following box we calculate all the other features defined in the first box. First of all, we set a limit time. If the time distance between two different flows is more than a threshold, we consider them as two different blocks. We use the same value provided in the paper since it has been proved experimentally that 95% of all packets arrive at most 4.43 seconds after their predecessors. Then we iterate over the dataset to calculate the following features:

Num_flow = number of flow in a block¶

Position = the index of the flow in a block¶

Duration = Duration in time of the block¶

Shift_from_start = difference in time between the current flow and the first flow in a block¶

Avg_flow_length = (max time in the block - min time in block)/duration¶

Mean_block = mean combining all the mean of the flow in a block¶

Var_block = variance combining all the variance of the flow in a block¶

In [5]:
limit = 4.5

for index, row in app.iterrows():
    if(index==0):
        begin = 0
        sum_length = row['flow_length']
        flow_min =  row['flow_start']
        flow_max = row['flow_start']
        mean_block = row['mean']
        var_bloc = row['variance']
    else:
        current = float(row['flow_start'])
        previous = float(app['flow_start'][index-1])
         
    if((index>0 and current>(previous+limit)) or (index==app.shape[0]-1)):
        
        if(current>previous+limit):
            end = index 
        if(index==app.shape[0]-1): #last element
            if(current<previous+limit):
                end = index+1
            #proper classification for last flow of dataframe    
            else:
                app.at[index,'Num_flow'] = 1
                app.at[index,'Duration'] = 0
                app.at[index,'Avg_flow_length'] = app['flow_length'][index]  
                app.at[index,'Mean_block'] = mean_block
                app.at[index,'Var_block'] = var_bloc
                app.at[index,'Position'] = 0
                app.at[index,'Shift_from_start'] = 0
        #print("index ",index," end ",end," begin ", begin)
        if(end-begin == 1):            
            app.at[begin,'Num_flow'] = 1
            app.at[begin,'Duration'] = 0
            app.at[begin,'Avg_flow_length'] = app['flow_length'][begin]  
            app.at[begin,'Mean_block'] = mean_block
            app.at[begin,'Var_block'] = var_bloc
            app.at[begin,'Position'] = 0
            app.at[begin,'Shift_from_start'] = 0
            begin = index
            continue
            
        duration = flow_max - flow_min
        number = end-begin
        avg = sum_length/number
        counter = 0
        first_flow = app['flow_start'][begin]        
        for j in range(begin,end):           
            app.at[j,'Num_flow'] = number
            app.at[j,'Duration'] = duration
            app.at[j,'Avg_flow_length'] = avg
            app.at[j,'Mean_block'] = float(mean_block/number)
            app.at[j,'Var_block'] = float(var_bloc/number)
            app.at[j,'Position']=counter
            app.at[j,'Shift_from_start'] = app['flow_start'][j] - first_flow
            counter+=1
            
        begin = index
        sum_length = row['flow_length']
        flow_min =  float(row['flow_start'])
        flow_max = float(row['flow_start'])
        mean_block = float(row['mean'])
        var_bloc = float(row['variance'])
    else:
        if(float(row['flow_start'])>flow_max):
            flow_max = float(row['flow_start'])
        elif(float(row['flow_start'])<flow_min):
            flow_min = float(row['flow_start'])
        sum_length+= row['flow_length']
        mean_block += float(row['mean'])
        var_bloc += float(row['variance'])

In [10]:
#Create a dataframe to store accuracy for each action
temp=app.groupby(['action']).count().reset_index()

miss_for_label = temp[['action', 'app']].copy()
miss_for_label.columns = ['Action','Number of sample']
miss_for_label["Misclassification"] = 0

We need to define our accuracy function. We compute each predicted label of the model, that is the label which obtained the higher score by the decision trees. If the predicted label is different from the actual label, it will be counted as misclasified. Finally the accuracy is the portion of well-classified labels. In addiction, we display the time required by the algorithm for the prediction.

In [11]:
#First of all I compute the prediction made using the model trained
startTest = time.time()
Y_pred=rf.predict(X_test)
endTest = time.time()

print("Time occured for prediction %.2f" %float(endTest-startTest))

#To calcualte accuracy I count the number of misclassified label
#The result will be a number of values equals to the number of a class
#The prediction is the index related to the highest value
mis = 0
for index in range(0,Y_pred.shape[0]):
    predicted_label = np.argmax(Y_pred[index])
    real_label = np.argmax(Y_test[index])
    if(predicted_label != real_label):
        name_real = values[real_label]
        miss_for_label.loc[miss_for_label['Action'] == name_real, 'Misclassification'] = miss_for_label.loc[miss_for_label['Action'] == name_real]['Misclassification']+1
        mis += 1

miss_for_label['Accuracy'] = 100-miss_for_label['Misclassification']/miss_for_label['Number of sample']*100
print("Number of misclassified sample: ", mis)
print("Total sample: ",Y_pred.shape[0] )
print("Test Accuracy: %.2f" % (100-float(mis)/Y_pred.shape[0]*100))
print("Accuracy for each action is the following:")
miss_for_label

In [12]:
#This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
    
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Neural Network¶

We obtain the best result with the usage of the Random Forest, but the first trial was with the usage of a neural network. For the sake of completeness we report also the result and the graph with neural network.

We consider the Neural network with all the inital features. The labels related to each flow are the same of the previous model. We need to define the list as numpy array for Input of Neural Network

In [18]:
#Create the array with the dataframe
X=selected_features.values.tolist() # Features
Y=one_hot.values.tolist()  # Labels

# Split dataset into training set and test set
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.3)

Size of train set:  35223
Size of the test set:  15096
Number of classes:  20

We define the model of our NN. We use as activation function the relu for all the hidden layers. Activation function for the output layer is the softmax. We use also a dropout function in order to prevent overfitting. The metrics used for the loss was categorical_crossentropy and we use the accuracy as a metrics for the compiling of the model.

In [19]:
from sklearn.utils import shuffle 
from keras import models
from keras import layers

def NN_model():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation = "relu", input_shape=(selected_features.shape[1],)))
    
    # Hidden - Layers    
    model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation = "relu"))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3, noise_shape=None, seed=None))
    model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation = "relu"))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3, noise_shape=None, seed=None))
    model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation = "relu"))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3, noise_shape=None, seed=None))
    model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation = "relu"))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3, noise_shape=None, seed=None))
    
    # Output- Layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(num_classes, activation = "softmax"))
    
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model
